# Learning & Explanation Preferences

- When teaching new concepts, build solid gut-level intuition with concrete examples.
- Give alternative views and perspectives on the concept — not just one angle.
- Go for comprehensive responses; details are welcome, not a burden.
- When explaining difficult concepts (like a formula), give concrete, simple examples to ground the abstraction.
- Ask questions or give problems to check understanding. No passive learning — real understanding comes from doing exercises.
